A basis for the row space 
                     V
                   of 
                     \Mtrx{A}
                   is given by the nonzero rows of 
                     \Mtrx{B}
                  ; therefore 
                     \Dim{ V }=\Rnk{ \Mtrx{A} }
                  .

A basis for the column space 
                     W
                   of 
                     \Mtrx{A}
                   is given by selecting from 
                     \Mtrx{A}
                   the column vectors in those positions in which 
                     \Mtrx{B}
                   has a leading 
                     1
                  . Therefore, 
                     \Dim{ W }=\Rnk{ \Mtrx{A} }
                  .

The argument consists of two parts. In the first part we show that 
                     \Mtrx{A}
                   and 
                     \Mtrx{B}
                   have the same row space. This is accomplished by showing that a row operation leaves the row space unchanged. In the second part of the argument we show that the nonzero row vectors of 
                     \Mtrx{B}
                   are linearly independent. â€“ Here are the details.
